                    <span>In the midst of raging anxiety, I find 400 page a little overwhelming. While it is comforting to learn as much as possible about the condition that is affecting you, I would personally recommend starting with a more practical approach (I benefited from the SelfTherapy.org approach - a simple method of managing anxiety through inner awareness), and then follow up with a book like this one. Good luck - the search for relief from anxiety is well worth it!</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Heal thyself with this book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>8</span>
                      /
                      <span>8</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-09-26</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>No one asks for a panic attack, but you certainly remember the first one: rapid breathing, quickened heartrate and the absolute certainty that you are tettering on the brink of death or psychosis. Suddenly the world becomes a checklist of things to avoid. The ultimate end of all panic attacks are you huddled in your bedroom, paralyzed with fear of everything and nothing all at once. Don't Panic cured me of this.
<br />
<br />For those who aren't so sure about drugs or wary of therapy, this book provides you with concrete, pratical solutions of regaining your life. There is no psycho-babble or esoteric theorums - only real-life psychology and application. The way Reid Wilson guides you through your panic struck me as almost psychic in nature. The most important thing to remember is that millions of people are suffering the *same* worries and doubts that you are at this very moment. There is no shame or humiliation in taking steps to remedy your problems, even though you will probably feel both with your panic attacks and when you buy this book.
<br />
<br />It's ironic...in your battles against panic attacks you'll hear the advice 'You've just got to get over it'. For the sufferer, this is his/her greatest dream, yet it seems constantly out of reach. Some reviewers tell that this book made them worse; the book itself explains why this is. When you talk of your fears, its only natural that they'll get inflamed at first. Ultimately it's a step on the path to recovery, and recovery isn't always easy. A final note: obsessive-compulsive disorder mirrors the symptoms of panic attacks in many ways. That's worth noting for some of you. The same author offers a book on that topic. If you've found your way here, you're halfway home. I'd recommend also to start taking Vitamin B tablets - no joke.</span>
                  
              
